<TITLE> No politicking in probe: Faruk </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 30 (bdnews24.com)Minister Muhammad Faruk Khan has brushed aside allegations that politics played a part in who was being questioned by criminal investigators into the BDR mutiny. "Those who are making such allegations are themselves involved in this incident," Faruk Khan retorted when a reporter of Diganta television drew his attention Monday to allegation that some were being "politically harassed" in the name of questioning. The minister's statement followed more than three hours of grilling Monday morning by the CID of a prominent Jamaat e Islami leader. Abdur Razzaq, a barrister, had moved the High Court the day before trying to avoid the CID appearance, but could only win an order not to arrest him until April 5. "Anyone suspected to have any links to the incidents will be interrogated," the minister said. "Already, 450 have been questioned. This is all part of the investigation," he said. "New evidence is emerging now ... We'll seek assistance from Interpol if necessary," he told reporters after attending a ceremony in Dhaka to mark 25 years of the British NGO, Action Aid
